This paper deals with the complexity of query evaluation in SPARQL, which is a query language for RDF data. Therefore, it is likely to belong to the cs.DB (databases) sub-category. Additionally, the paper introduces a new notion of width called domination width, which relies on the well-known notion of treewidth. This suggests that the paper may also be relevant to the cs.AI (artificial intelligence) sub-category, which often deals with graph-based algorithms and data structures. The paper also discusses the complexity of evaluating queries using the AND, OPTIONAL, and UNION operators, which suggests that it may be relevant to the cs.DS (data structures and algorithms) sub-category. Furthermore, the paper presents a structural characterization of the classes of well-designed queries that can be evaluated in polynomial time, which suggests that it may be relevant to the cs.LG (machine learning) sub-category, which often deals with the complexity of learning algorithms. Finally, the paper discusses complexity theoretic assumptions, which suggests that it may be relevant to the cs.CC (computational complexity) sub-category.
